{"key":"post-16435107","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16435107</id>\n<content>The grains should not have been placed on the perlite.&amp;nbsp; The perlite is only to supply humidity.&amp;nbsp; By placing grains on perlite, they're attempting to colonize it, but there is no food source there.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you want to fruit grains, you're supposed to put the fully colonized grains in a tray, and then place your casing layer over that, and then set the tray above the perlite.&amp;nbsp; Even better is to mix the colonized grains with a bulk substrate such as manure, and then fruit it either cased or uncased.&amp;nbsp; Take a look at the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Horse-Manure-Substrate&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;manure preparation video&lt;/a&gt; to see how the latter is done.&amp;nbsp; You'll also find a casing layer preparation video and the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;shotgun terrarium fruiting chamber&lt;/a&gt; tek at the same place.&amp;nbsp; Good luck.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>16435074</prev>\n<first>16430754</first>\n<last>16435107</last>\n<when>1340641049</when>\n<utime>06/25/12 07:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}